            body: 'Operating systems use multiple mechanisms to prevent processes from accessing memory they do not own and to stop malicious code execution.',
            list: [
              'Segmentation — divides memory into named segments (code, data, stack) with defined access permissions (read, write, execute); hardware enforces boundary violations.',
              'Paging — breaks physical memory into fixed-size pages; the OS controls access via the page table; provides virtual memory abstraction.',
              'Virtual Memory — allows processes to use address spaces larger than physical RAM; OS swaps pages to disk; prevents direct process-to-process interference.',
              'Data Execution Prevention (DEP / NX bit) — marks memory pages as either executable OR writable, not both; prevents shellcode injection into data regions.',
              'Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR) — randomizes the base addresses of the stack, heap, and libraries at each execution; makes exploitation of memory corruption bugs significantly harder.',
            ],
